What are Control Flow Statements?

Control flow statements decide:

Which command should run

When a command should run

How many times a command should run

They help the script make decisions and repeat tasks automatically.

Why We Use Control Flow Statements

We use control flow statements to:

1️⃣ Make decisions in scripts
Example: check if a file exists.

2️⃣ Repeat tasks automatically
Example: create multiple directories.

3️⃣ Control program execution
Example: run different commands for different conditions.

Example Without Control Flow
echo "Hello"
echo "Hello"
echo "Hello"
echo "Hello"

This repeats the same command many times.

Example With Control Flow (Loop)
for i in 1 2 3 4
do
 echo "Hello"
done

Here the loop controls how many times the command runs.

Common Control Flow Statements in Shell Script
Statement	Purpose
if	Check a condition
if-else	Choose between two conditions
case	Multiple conditions
for	Repeat a task
while	Run while condition is true
until	Run until condition becomes true

✅ Short Definition

Control flow statements are commands in Bash that control the execution order of a script by making decisions or repeating tasks.

